text: He had a shot in 2014, at 27, but the Germans were too resilient. He had another shot in 2015, but the Chileans, in their home country, held the Argentines and won on Penalties. For the third year in a row, and again against the Chileans, he was that close to finally winning, but pressure caught up and blasted his penalty wide. This was when he 'retired' from his country. However, in 2017,  in a period of darkness all around him, Edgardo Bauza, encouraged him to return back. 2018 may have been a bad year, and the same with 2019, but in 2021, he finally won a title with his country, beating their rivals Brazil. He won another in 2022, the Finallsima, against Italy at Wembley. And finally, in December, one man by the name of Gonzalo Montiel, secured a 3rd title but a final step. This made Messi an undisputed GOAT.

text: The greatest final, yes, but not the greatest match ever, that remains the Italy/Germany semi final in 1970.  Had this final been settled with a fourth, (and the French nearly did get a winner) then this would have been both the greatest final and the greatest match.  Up to now the greatest final had been the Wembley story, not now.   1970 had the greatest game, save (Gordon Banks from Pele), tackle (Bobby Moore on Jairzinho), miss (twice - both by Pele), player (need you ask), goal (Carlos Alberto in the final), and team (need you ask), and will remain a yardstick by which all world cups will be measured.

text:
QATARâ€™S HOSTING OF THE WORLD CUP

 The first problem is the desire to join them in their play and amusement. A lifestyle foreign to Islam and bigger than just the game.

 Loyalty to Islam is replaced by loyalty to team or country and friendships and enmity is based on this rather than iman and kufr.

 The environment created is completely haraam from the kits worn to the mixing in the stands, the music, advertising and culture.

 Qatar cannot try to garnish the haraam with some ayaat and selective application of laws rooted in sharia and think that makes the event halaal.

 They desire the lifestyle of the kufaar, hanker after it, even bribe to get to host it and expose the Muslims in their lands to all the evil, but expect that islam â€œas a cultureâ€ should be respected on par with all other â€œculturesâ€- is Islam a culture? Is it equal to other religions or lifestyles? Is it not the truth? Or is their version the cultural one?

 They claim to be doing dawah bringing in Zakir Naik and adding ayaat to the proceedings- stopping for salaah etc- would it be ok to host the worlds biggest music festival or open a nightclub in order to give dawah to those that will attend. Supplying everything needed for the haraam but pretending that the true intention is to spread Islam- does that even make sense?

Allowing alcohol outside the stadium instead of inside- how is that not compromising deeni principles? 
 

Is it even appropriate to recite ayaat inbetween music, or have hadith on every corner when the entire event is an affront to Allah and his Rasool â€ (ï·º) .Right and wrong are no longer clear- everything is mixed up and given an Islamic flavor- far more dangerous than doing the wrong and seeing it for what it is. This is confusing the common Muslim.

 He is unwittingly supporting Qatar because he thinks they are standing up for the deen - but he forgets that the whole event that Qatar is hosting is haraam and what they seemed to be standing up for was compromised anyway. This has absolutely nothing to do with the deen. It is fasad. 

If you donâ€™t accept that the game itself and its environment are wrong then you will not be able to see the bigger picture and how the deen of Allah is being sold for a paltry price.

 While we are busy playing footsie with the kufaar on the field they are bombing our brothers and sisters, children and parents in other parts of the world and legislating against Islam in their countries and muslim counties where their henchman dictators do it on their behalf.

But who wants to know about all that and how we should be fighting against the kufaar instead of playing with them and talking harmony- why look at our real obligation when we can enjoy being distracted by a game and live in an artificial reality created by them to keep us busy so we donâ€™t realize whatâ€™s happening and fighting them (as we should be) is the furthest thing from our minds.

After all they even have Muslim prop players to soften our hearts and make us find deeni excuses to be involved in the religion of football - do we really believe they are there for dawah and that we have more impact on the kufaar then they have on us? When mo salah celebrates christmas or fondles with a model on gq magazine- who is influencing who- is he the daâ€™ee we celebrate?

 The shaytaani symbolism are many and openly on show. Look at the arm stretching between the Morgan freeeman and the disabled hafidh imitating the â€œthe creation of Adamâ€ painting by Michaelangelo and recreating his role as â€œGodâ€ from the movie â€œBruce Almightyâ€ - with the kaafir above the muslim as his God- how symbolic. Look at the jinn mascot who openly talks about a different dimension that existed before man and the emphasis on Magic - the entire concept is from the occult and open to see. 

 But despite all the above which is clear and apparent, the ingrained love for soccer and our hearts attachment to their sport, their leagues, their brands , their celebrity- will not allow us to recognize the wrong and repent. Even if we are caught up, atleast to make tawbah. Instead we go into defence mode and blame the â€œbackwardâ€ ulema because we find other ulema who are more â€œwith itâ€, who endorse it and tell us it is ok. Beyond our infatuation with it, if we look deep into our hearts do we really think there is nothing wrong with the sport and everything that surrounds it? Is the real mufti (our heart) so consumed by the love of things of this dunya that it is no longer able to see clear haraam being masked with a veneer of halaal?

We have lost our way as an ummah and we desire to only follow those who will endorse our lifestyle , which is in effect the same as the lifestyle of the kufaar. Little separates us nowadays and we are lucky if we are eating and drinking halaal. The rest is the same. If there is nothing wrong with this and the ulema who rubber stamp it and participate in it are correct can you imagine if Nabi â€ (ï·º) and the sahabah were here today would they be attending the World Cup? do you think they would be encouraging inter faith or looking at ways to bridge the gap harmoniously between the Muslims and the kufaar? Is that the sunnah?

 Think deeply about it- not only in regard to the soccer but our entire lives- before dismissing those few ulema who are trying desperately to save us from the fire by warning us and encouraging us and those who are fighting the fight against kufr and assimilation. Who are standing up for the deen despite the harsh and negative responses they get. Not dissimilar to ambiya who kept reminding and warning their people. Even if you are not strong enough to fight for the deen atleast accept that wrong is wrong and right is right- so that you can atleast repent. Aspire to change and even if we are weak, stand for the right things - the only thing worth giving your life and wealth for- this gift of Imaan and the deen that our Nabi â€ (ï·º) took 23 difficult years to bring to us. Donâ€™t throw it away because the lifestyle they sold you is now too ingrained in you to change. Itâ€™s never too late.

May Allah strengthen us all, grant us istiqamah on the Haq and guide us on the siraatul mustaqeem

author: @KenanLaudat-tp3bp

text:
@@KenanLaudat-tp3bp That's what Wikipedia says...

"Association Football" (the actual name of the sport) was shortened by "Assoc -er" ("soccer").

It's a British shortened term...
author: @davepazz580

text:
â€‹@davepazz580  I wasn't saying that wasn't the name. I was just confused about how you could get soccer from association football.
It makes more sense now, but it's still a bit confusing.
author: @KenanLaudat-tp3bp

text:
@@KenanLaudat-tp3bp From what I recall, there was a trend in Britain to shorten some words by adding an "-er" at the end of some words... so "breakfast" became "breakker".

So they took the "Association" and isolated the "socc" and added the "er" and it became soccer.

Funny thing is if you go back and watch some old British programs from the 60's or before then, they will say "soccer" when referring to the game.

text:
Liberal hypocrisy
When England hosted the World Cup in 1966, homosexuality was still illegal, and remained so in Scotland until 1980 and in Northern Ireland until 1982. When the law was finally amended, it merely "decriminalised private homosexual acts between men aged over 21, while at the same time imposing heavier penalties on street offences". 

As for workersâ€™ rights, ongoing discrimination against non-white workers was rampant, including in British trade unions. 
Britain maintained its colonial holdings across the globe, from the then defiant white settler-colony of Rhodesia to Hong Kong and the Malvinas (Falkland) Islands to what were yet recent crimes against the Kenyan people who had just obtained independence in 1963. They were of little concern to human rights defenders. 

Qatar itself was at the time under British colonial rule.

Britain then, as now, still had blasphemy laws and the Church of England remains its official religion. Still, it hosted the World Cup without complaint from Europeâ€™s civil libertarians, least of all from Amnesty International.

In 1974, when West Germany hosted the World Cup, the population in that country was experiencing its latest wave of government repression. 

In 1972 the West German government began to purge "radicals" from the civil service (which then included 20 percent of the West German workforce). West German trade unions routinely expelled "activist" members. The Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution investigated 2.5 million citizens. 

In fact, 800,000 applicants for civil service jobs were investigated regarding their â€œallegianceâ€ to the constitution. A policy of blacklisting, or "Berufsverbot" - for signing petitions, joining demonstrations, etc - of those deemed guilty ensued. 


A crackdown on universities, dismissal of teachers, and â€œvoluntaryâ€ withdrawals of â€œquestionableâ€ books by publishers was the order of the day. Whereas Nazi anti-homosexual laws, which remained on the books, were repealed in 1969, official anti-homosexual discrimination continued in the country until 2000.

West German racism against Turkish migrant labour was also rampant. Indeed, most of the leadership of West Germanyâ€™s Justice Ministry between 1949 and 1973 were former members of the Nazi party, including dozens of former paramilitary SA members. 
But West Germany hosted the World Cup without complaint from Europeâ€™s civil libertarians, least of all Amnesty International (which was urged to intervene on behalf of the Baader-Meinhof prisoners who staged a hunger strike in German prisons, protesting against torture. Amnesty refused to adopt them, as allegations of torture, in Amnestyâ€™s estimation, were not â€œjustifiedâ€.)  

When the World Cup was held in the United States in 1994, half the US states had anti-sodomy and anti-homosexual laws, and the widely disseminated claim that Aids was a "gay disease" had not yet subsided. The country was proceeding at the time with its sanctions against Iraq, which led to the death of half a million Iraqi children. 

Police killing and beating of black men on the streets of US cities became a public scandal in 1991, when the video of police violence against Rodney King in Los Angeles went viral. This aside from the ongoing New Jim Crow system of incarcerating Black people in US prisons, to which the Bill Clinton administration contributed significantly; the use of prisoners as slave labour as permitted by the 13th amendment to the US constitution, and the ongoing violation of Native American rights. 

But the US hosted the World Cup without complaint from European and US civil libertarians, least of all Amnesty International (whose report that year criticised the death penalty, and police brutality, and the forcible return of Haitian refugees, but not anti-homosexual laws, let alone the abuse of migrant workers, etc).
